WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.550 --> 00:00:04.260
ALEX: Welcome to this event.

00:00:04.260 --> 00:00:08.420
Another series in the Gayglers
pride month, so happy pride

00:00:08.420 --> 00:00:10.490
month everyone!

00:00:10.490 --> 00:00:11.510
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:11.510 --> 00:00:14.090
ALEX: Pride is in fact the
entire month long, and not

00:00:14.090 --> 00:00:16.640
just one debaucherous weekend.

00:00:16.640 --> 00:00:21.640
So it's my pleasure today
to introduce two leading

00:00:21.640 --> 00:00:25.460
advocates in the gay civil
rights movement, Kris Perry

00:00:25.460 --> 00:00:26.770
and Sandy Stier.

00:00:26.770 --> 00:00:29.290
They have been at the forefront
of the Prop 8

00:00:29.290 --> 00:00:33.760
litigation battle and we're very
honored to have them with

00:00:33.760 --> 00:00:34.940
us here today.

00:00:34.940 --> 00:00:39.500
They've been together since '97,
were married in 2004, and

00:00:39.500 --> 00:00:41.410
have raised-- perhaps their
greatest achievement--

00:00:41.410 --> 00:00:43.610
four boys together.

00:00:43.610 --> 00:00:46.580
The two youngest ones just
graduated last weekend.

00:00:46.580 --> 00:00:51.990
Just in time to recognize
Supreme Court decisions that

00:00:51.990 --> 00:00:55.140
will be coming down next week.

00:00:55.140 --> 00:00:58.780
The Supreme Court is taking
their time and is going to

00:00:58.780 --> 00:01:02.320
roll out momentous decisions
altogether next week on gay

00:01:02.320 --> 00:01:05.420
marriage, Voting Rights Act,
affirmative action.

00:01:05.420 --> 00:01:07.420
So next week is going
to be very exciting.

00:01:07.420 --> 00:01:10.750
Kris is executive director of
the First Five Years Fund,

00:01:10.750 --> 00:01:13.750
which is a national organization
that focuses on

00:01:13.750 --> 00:01:17.450
investments in quality early
childhood education programs

00:01:17.450 --> 00:01:19.100
for disadvantaged children.

00:01:19.100 --> 00:01:22.520
And Sandy, on the far right, is
a director of information

00:01:22.520 --> 00:01:27.170
systems for Alameda County
Health Care Services Agency.

00:01:27.170 --> 00:01:29.330
And I'm not going to tell you
too much about their story,

00:01:29.330 --> 00:01:32.340
because they're going to do a
much better job of telling it

00:01:32.340 --> 00:01:33.640
themselves.

00:01:33.640 --> 00:01:35.160
So I'll hand it off
to you guys.

00:01:35.160 --> 00:01:36.540
Thank you so much.

00:01:36.540 --> 00:01:38.540
SANDY STIER: Thank you
for having us.

00:01:38.540 --> 00:01:42.870
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:42.870 --> 00:01:44.650
SANDY STIER: So first of all,
I'd like to say, if you want

00:01:44.650 --> 00:01:46.600
to call Kris, "Perry,"
feel free.

00:01:46.600 --> 00:01:49.730
Because she is now known as
"Perry" to the broader

00:01:49.730 --> 00:01:51.270
community and to the media.

00:01:51.270 --> 00:01:53.760
We're so happy to be here and to
talk to you about where we

00:01:53.760 --> 00:01:56.770
are with the case for
marriage equality.

00:01:56.770 --> 00:01:58.960
It's been a great journey
and an exciting one.

00:01:58.960 --> 00:02:01.530
And we feel very privileged to
get to be in the position of

00:02:01.530 --> 00:02:04.770
representing such an important
civil rights issue.

00:02:04.770 --> 00:02:07.640
Today we'd like to take you
through some different parts

00:02:07.640 --> 00:02:09.830
of the case and show you
a couple video clips.

00:02:09.830 --> 00:02:10.740
Hopefully they'll
be interesting.

00:02:10.740 --> 00:02:13.720
We want to use most of our time
for Q&amp;A to hear from you

00:02:13.720 --> 00:02:17.050
and get a better idea of what
your questions are, and what

00:02:17.050 --> 00:02:21.820
your concerns are, and how you
view this particular case.

00:02:21.820 --> 00:02:24.860
So starting off, we have this
picture of us in front of the

00:02:24.860 --> 00:02:25.970
Supreme Court.

00:02:25.970 --> 00:02:28.650
We were there in March
of this year.

00:02:28.650 --> 00:02:30.940
The transcripts are
available online.

00:02:30.940 --> 00:02:32.310
You can Google them
if you want to.

00:02:32.310 --> 00:02:33.640
They're quite interesting.

00:02:33.640 --> 00:02:37.250
We were there with our kids and
our legal team, including

00:02:37.250 --> 00:02:39.700
Enrique Monagas, who is
here with us today.

00:02:39.700 --> 00:02:41.960
So he's going to help field some
of the legal questions,

00:02:41.960 --> 00:02:44.230
if you have anything
you want to ask.

00:02:44.230 --> 00:02:46.600
And let's go ahead
and get going.

00:02:46.600 --> 00:02:50.300
KRIS PERRY: So nothing of this
scale and scope is possible

00:02:50.300 --> 00:02:51.630
with just a couple of people.

00:02:51.630 --> 00:02:55.400
We're part of a really large
team, made up of funders, and

00:02:55.400 --> 00:02:57.220
attorneys, and advocates.

00:02:57.220 --> 00:03:00.650
What you see here before you
are just a sampling of the

00:03:00.650 --> 00:03:01.850
people that have been
invested in this

00:03:01.850 --> 00:03:03.120
from the very beginning.

00:03:03.120 --> 00:03:06.370
The Reiners, Michelle and Rob
Reiner, along with Dustin

00:03:06.370 --> 00:03:09.630
Lance Black, and Bruce Cohen
and Cleve Jones, are on the

00:03:09.630 --> 00:03:11.820
board of the American Foundation
for Equal Rights.

00:03:11.820 --> 00:03:14.820
And have made it their mission
to not only contribute

00:03:14.820 --> 00:03:17.730
financially, but to help others
contribute financially.

00:03:17.730 --> 00:03:20.360
And that, in fact, has been
one of the most important

00:03:20.360 --> 00:03:21.560
roles in this.

00:03:21.560 --> 00:03:24.470
A case that takes four years
to travel through the legal

00:03:24.470 --> 00:03:27.990
system generates some legal
fees, even when people are

00:03:27.990 --> 00:03:30.740
being generous with their time,
including pro bono.

00:03:30.740 --> 00:03:33.860
But those board members have
done a huge amount to help

00:03:33.860 --> 00:03:34.890
this movement.

00:03:34.890 --> 00:03:37.440
And then above them, you can see
the other plaintiffs, Jeff

00:03:37.440 --> 00:03:39.690
and Paul, next to Chad Griffin,
who has since moved

00:03:39.690 --> 00:03:41.300
on to the human rights
campaign.

00:03:41.300 --> 00:03:44.420
And our attorneys, David Boies
and Ted Olson, along with

00:03:44.420 --> 00:03:47.310
Christina Shockey and Adam
Umhoefer, who are also some of

00:03:47.310 --> 00:03:48.710
the founding members
of the American

00:03:48.710 --> 00:03:50.100
Foundation of Equal Rights.

00:03:50.100 --> 00:03:54.220
But one of more fun stories in
all of this is how did Sandy

00:03:54.220 --> 00:03:56.620
and I actually come to be
a part of this team?

00:03:56.620 --> 00:03:57.730
We are not Hollywood

00:03:57.730 --> 00:04:00.810
A-listers, we are not attorneys.

00:04:00.810 --> 00:04:04.720
And we are not long-time,
legendary, gay rights

00:04:04.720 --> 00:04:06.330
activists like Cleve Jones.

00:04:06.330 --> 00:04:09.120
We are, in fact, just ordinary
people that were busy raising

00:04:09.120 --> 00:04:11.140
our families and going
to work every day.

00:04:11.140 --> 00:04:14.270
When we learned that there was
possibly going to be a

00:04:14.270 --> 00:04:15.690
challenge to Proposition 8.

00:04:15.690 --> 00:04:18.120
And we learned that through our
friend, Chad Griffin, who

00:04:18.120 --> 00:04:20.720
at the time, was working with
Rob Reiner in Los Angeles on a

00:04:20.720 --> 00:04:22.380
number of other political
issues.

00:04:22.380 --> 00:04:24.680
Not the least of which was early
childhood education,

00:04:24.680 --> 00:04:27.320
which is what I have dedicated
my career toward.

00:04:27.320 --> 00:04:30.480
And I was on a phone call with
Chad just out of the blue one

00:04:30.480 --> 00:04:33.090
day, and he mentioned that he
was putting a group of people

00:04:33.090 --> 00:04:34.620
together because they were
really upset about how

00:04:34.620 --> 00:04:36.230
Proposition 8 had passed.

00:04:36.230 --> 00:04:38.580
And I asked him a little bit
about it and he said, well,

00:04:38.580 --> 00:04:41.540
Rob and I were at lunch with
Michelle and we were talking

00:04:41.540 --> 00:04:42.530
about how angry we were.

00:04:42.530 --> 00:04:45.140
And if you know the Reiners,
they tend to be rather loud.

00:04:45.140 --> 00:04:46.720
So apparently, they
were overheard.

00:04:46.720 --> 00:04:49.850
And they were overheard at the
polo lounge by someone that

00:04:49.850 --> 00:04:52.670
used to be related to Ted Olson,
a former sister-in-law.

00:04:52.670 --> 00:04:56.110
And she came over and said, you
may not believe this, but

00:04:56.110 --> 00:04:58.430
there is someone in Washington
DC who cares about this, who

00:04:58.430 --> 00:04:59.760
would probably help you.

00:04:59.760 --> 00:05:00.750
And they said, who?

00:05:00.750 --> 00:05:03.000
And she said, Ted Olson.

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:04.460
And they all said, really?

00:05:04.460 --> 00:05:06.740
Ted Olson, as in "Bush
v. Gore" Ted Olson?

00:05:06.740 --> 00:05:08.120
And they said, yes.

00:05:08.120 --> 00:05:09.930
And that's how this all began.

00:05:09.930 --> 00:05:12.300
Chad knew me, Chad ended
up meeting Ted.

00:05:12.300 --> 00:05:15.100
I know Sandy.

00:05:15.100 --> 00:05:16.560
And we ended up--

00:05:16.560 --> 00:05:19.920
we lived together, we actually
know each other quite well--

00:05:19.920 --> 00:05:25.020
and so really, these things came
together rather quickly,

00:05:25.020 --> 00:05:26.280
these relationships.

00:05:26.280 --> 00:05:29.560
And I wanted to be sure that you
understood how we ended up

00:05:29.560 --> 00:05:32.030
in this, because we are not
like the rest of them.

00:05:32.030 --> 00:05:34.380
ALEX: And can you walk us
through your decision making

00:05:34.380 --> 00:05:35.450
process on that a little bit?

00:05:35.450 --> 00:05:38.460
Because I think here we've
got a room of some young,

00:05:38.460 --> 00:05:42.800
aspiring, perhaps future civil
rights leaders here.

00:05:42.800 --> 00:05:45.700
And it takes a lot of courage
to put yourself in the

00:05:45.700 --> 00:05:49.460
spotlight, put your
name on the line.

00:05:49.460 --> 00:05:52.900
What was your decision making
process in deciding to step up

00:05:52.900 --> 00:05:53.380
and do that?

00:05:53.380 --> 00:05:56.190
I mean there are lots of angry
people out there, but it's

00:05:56.190 --> 00:05:58.000
really easy to be angry
in our living rooms.

00:05:58.000 --> 00:05:59.130
SANDY STIER: Yeah, well
we're particularly

00:05:59.130 --> 00:06:00.600
angry, because we have--

00:06:00.600 --> 00:06:01.660
as we said, a lot of
kids-- and so we're

00:06:01.660 --> 00:06:04.200
mad most of the time.

00:06:04.200 --> 00:06:05.550
It's getting better
now that they're

00:06:05.550 --> 00:06:07.140
graduating and moving on.

00:06:07.140 --> 00:06:10.590
But it was actually a fairly
quick and easy decision for us

00:06:10.590 --> 00:06:11.100
on some level.

00:06:11.100 --> 00:06:14.090
And it's really because we felt
so strongly that marriage

00:06:14.090 --> 00:06:16.650
should be available to us and
to everybody in our country.

00:06:16.650 --> 00:06:19.730
And that voting on our rights
just seem completely

00:06:19.730 --> 00:06:20.920
fundamentally wrong.

00:06:20.920 --> 00:06:23.940
So we had such a problem with
Proposition 8 being on the

00:06:23.940 --> 00:06:25.050
ballot in the first place.

00:06:25.050 --> 00:06:27.440
Even being part of the voting
process and it didn't make any

00:06:27.440 --> 00:06:28.000
sense to us.

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:30.420
And then when we heard about
this possible legal challenge,

00:06:30.420 --> 00:06:33.460
we both said, oh my gosh,
what a great place

00:06:33.460 --> 00:06:35.230
to address the issue.

00:06:35.230 --> 00:06:36.620
We have to be protected.

00:06:36.620 --> 00:06:37.440
We're a minority, we need to be

00:06:37.440 --> 00:06:38.840
protected from the majority.

00:06:38.840 --> 00:06:41.690
So for us, as individuals, I
think we both came fairly

00:06:41.690 --> 00:06:45.620
quickly to feel very supportive
of this initiative,

00:06:45.620 --> 00:06:47.530
approaching it in this way.

00:06:47.530 --> 00:06:50.420
In terms of the family, we
decided, between the two of

00:06:50.420 --> 00:06:51.890
us, that we felt comfortable
moving forward.

00:06:51.890 --> 00:06:52.870
And we believed in it.

00:06:52.870 --> 00:06:54.580
And we thought it was the right
team, and the right

00:06:54.580 --> 00:06:56.110
challenge, and the
right players.

00:06:56.110 --> 00:06:59.940
And then we just went down the
row of kids and asked each one

00:06:59.940 --> 00:07:01.670
individually, how would
you feel about it?

00:07:01.670 --> 00:07:05.430
Because we felt strongly that if
any one of the boys didn't

00:07:05.430 --> 00:07:08.200
feel comfortable with our being
involved in it, that we

00:07:08.200 --> 00:07:08.730
wouldn't do it.

00:07:08.730 --> 00:07:10.130
Because it does impact
them, as well.

00:07:10.130 --> 00:07:12.730
Even though they're tangential,
there's no way of

00:07:12.730 --> 00:07:14.680
getting out of the fact that
it does impact them.

00:07:14.680 --> 00:07:17.170
And the boys were all really
very supportive.

00:07:17.170 --> 00:07:19.720
In part, because they are
somewhat narcissistic, to be

00:07:19.720 --> 00:07:22.570
totally honest.

00:07:22.570 --> 00:07:23.840
What do you think about
us being in the case?

00:07:23.840 --> 00:07:25.210
Well, that's fine, but
I need some money.

00:07:25.210 --> 00:07:26.810
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:26.810 --> 00:07:29.860
SANDY STIER: Like, OK.

00:07:29.860 --> 00:07:32.190
And yeah, I believe it and I
think it's the right thing to

00:07:32.190 --> 00:07:34.280
do, but I'm not saying that just
for you, I'm saying it

00:07:34.280 --> 00:07:34.610
for society.

00:07:34.610 --> 00:07:36.550
I'm like, OK, be politically
correct.

00:07:36.550 --> 00:07:37.440
That's totally fine.

00:07:37.440 --> 00:07:40.580
So the boys were supportive of
it and that was all we needed.

00:07:40.580 --> 00:07:42.520
We didn't really look for
anybody else's approval, we

00:07:42.520 --> 00:07:44.650
didn't check in with the
rest of our families.

00:07:44.650 --> 00:07:45.870
Just our kids and each other.

00:07:45.870 --> 00:07:47.230
And then we moved forward.

00:07:47.230 --> 00:07:51.410
KRIS PERRY: The courage part,
though, is sometimes, you can

00:07:51.410 --> 00:07:54.980
mistake thinking you're signing
up for something that

00:07:54.980 --> 00:07:57.670
was more like the other
challenges had been, which is

00:07:57.670 --> 00:08:01.000
more of an administrative
process that seemed--

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:03.610
actually it was still a big
leap of faith for us to be

00:08:03.610 --> 00:08:06.420
involved in something that
would've been more about a

00:08:06.420 --> 00:08:07.730
paper-driven driven process--

00:08:07.730 --> 00:08:10.210
but it became a very
people-driven process.

00:08:10.210 --> 00:08:13.770
And I feel really fortunate that
we were supported by a

00:08:13.770 --> 00:08:17.630
group of lawyers and advocates
that really helped us move

00:08:17.630 --> 00:08:21.700
from something more quiet to
something a little bit louder.

00:08:21.700 --> 00:08:24.170
And I would just say to all of
you, as you go through your

00:08:24.170 --> 00:08:27.070
lives and you find yourself in
situations where you feel that

00:08:27.070 --> 00:08:30.230
you have not been treated
fairly, and you have not been

00:08:30.230 --> 00:08:34.460
given protection, and you are
not in a situation that is

00:08:34.460 --> 00:08:37.580
really acceptable to you, there
are numerous ways to

00:08:37.580 --> 00:08:38.640
resolve that problem.

00:08:38.640 --> 00:08:40.650
One of which is to hire lawyers
and go through the

00:08:40.650 --> 00:08:41.350
court system.

00:08:41.350 --> 00:08:43.179
But it is not the only way.

00:08:43.179 --> 00:08:46.140
And, in fact, if it weren't for
years and years, decades

00:08:46.140 --> 00:08:49.330
really, of other people standing
up, like Harvey Milk,

00:08:49.330 --> 00:08:51.490
and Cleve Jones, and
Phyllis and Del.

00:08:51.490 --> 00:08:55.320
And so many others fighting
back on a more political

00:08:55.320 --> 00:08:59.030
front, or through a grassroots
advocacy, a legal challenge

00:08:59.030 --> 00:09:01.350
would have seemed really
premature.

00:09:01.350 --> 00:09:02.820
Or really ill-advised.

00:09:02.820 --> 00:09:06.720
So it's really a combination
of events that lead to a

00:09:06.720 --> 00:09:08.570
moment in time, like this,
where we know that

00:09:08.570 --> 00:09:11.400
everything's pulling in favor
of gay marriage now.

00:09:11.400 --> 00:09:12.540
And so much is shifting.

00:09:12.540 --> 00:09:16.150
But it's really a rare time to
see a social movement happen

00:09:16.150 --> 00:09:17.570
within a few years.

00:09:17.570 --> 00:09:20.720
But it's really after
many years.

00:09:20.720 --> 00:09:24.590
So moving past who some of the
players are and where we've

00:09:24.590 --> 00:09:27.220
been, we wanted to talk a little
bit about what actually

00:09:27.220 --> 00:09:31.150
happened in that trial that we
ended up being a part of.

00:09:31.150 --> 00:09:34.160
There were many, many witnesses
for our side.

00:09:34.160 --> 00:09:37.750
People that came to court and
said, this is why Proposition

00:09:37.750 --> 00:09:40.890
8 is harmful and
unconstitutional.

00:09:40.890 --> 00:09:45.200
And the witnesses really were
on the full spectrum of

00:09:45.200 --> 00:09:51.560
experts from Yale and Harvard
and UC Berkeley and UC Davis.

00:09:51.560 --> 00:09:54.790
And people that had been
studying sociology and

00:09:54.790 --> 00:09:58.040
political power and on the
institution of marriage,

00:09:58.040 --> 00:09:59.605
frankly, for their
entire careers.

00:09:59.605 --> 00:10:03.710
They were there to testify on
behalf of our team, as well as

00:10:03.710 --> 00:10:07.060
laypeople, like Sandy and I,
Jeff and Paul, the mayor of

00:10:07.060 --> 00:10:11.610
San Diego, and even someone
that had been put through

00:10:11.610 --> 00:10:13.410
reparative therapy.

00:10:13.410 --> 00:10:17.500
So we had a great blend of real
stories from real people,

00:10:17.500 --> 00:10:23.500
as well as witnesses from
all over the world.

00:10:23.500 --> 00:10:26.990
The more telling piece of the
story was how few witnesses

00:10:26.990 --> 00:10:27.750
the other side had.

00:10:27.750 --> 00:10:30.830
And I'll let Sandy talk about
the two witnesses that the

00:10:30.830 --> 00:10:31.600
other side had.

00:10:31.600 --> 00:10:34.460
And just when you look at the
numbers, it comes out very

00:10:34.460 --> 00:10:36.160
unbalanced.

00:10:36.160 --> 00:10:38.710
SANDY STIER: Right so, there's
nothing like being on the

00:10:38.710 --> 00:10:39.740
winning team, right?

00:10:39.740 --> 00:10:43.490
And it was very clear in court
in no time that we were

00:10:43.490 --> 00:10:44.640
definitely on the
winning team.

00:10:44.640 --> 00:10:47.190
Not only did we have great
expert witnesses, but they

00:10:47.190 --> 00:10:51.510
talked about some of those
salient arguments that could

00:10:51.510 --> 00:10:55.570
be presented, in terms of
economics and the political

00:10:55.570 --> 00:10:58.620
process, and how really
under-represented gays are.

00:10:58.620 --> 00:11:01.950
And violence against gay people,
and how many different

00:11:01.950 --> 00:11:04.040
rights are associated with
marriage, including adoption,

00:11:04.040 --> 00:11:05.850
immigration, so many
different things.

00:11:05.850 --> 00:11:07.710
And how important it is
to have equality.

00:11:07.710 --> 00:11:09.520
Well, on the other side, they
really couldn't drum up any

00:11:09.520 --> 00:11:13.440
good expert witnesses, because
there really aren't any.

00:11:13.440 --> 00:11:15.260
The ones that they did bring
forth, number one was David

00:11:15.260 --> 00:11:17.490
